   rc = ldap_win_bind(data, server, user, passwd);Description: CVE-2026-8932: fix incomplete mTLS config in conn reuse and session cache
 Five client-credential fields (cert_type, key, key_type, key_passwd,
 key_blob) lived in ssl_config_data but not in ssl_primary_config, so
 they were invisible to match_ssl_primary_config() and to the TLS
 session-cache peer key. Two easy handles sharing a connection pool
 could reuse each other's authenticated connections when they differed
 only on SSLKEY, SSLKEYTYPE, KEYPASSWD, SSLCERTTYPE or SSLKEYBLOB. The
 second handle would silently inherit the first handle's identity
 (CWE-305, authentication bypass by primary weakness).
 .
 Promote the five fields into ssl_primary_config so the conn-reuse
 predicate and session-cache key cover the complete client-credential
 set. Also fold the client-cert / key / cert_type / key_type into the
 session-cache peer key (replacing the ":CCERT" marker), and add
 key_passwd to the peer-auth match check.
 .
 Every TLS backend that reads these fields is updated in lockstep:
 openssl, gnutls, mbedtls, rustls, schannel, wolfssl, and (target-only)
 sectransp. libssh/libssh2 and ldap are updated for the field move.
 .
 Backport notes for debian trixie curl 8.14.1:
  * Field references in target-only backend sectransp are updated in
    parallel (upstream removed sectransp before the fix; no upstream
    reference exists — done to keep the target compiling after the
    struct-layout change).
  * The upstream helper Curl_ssl_peer_key_build() and the accompanying
    unit3303/unit3304 tests are NOT backported: they depend on the
    unitcheck.h / peer.h / struct Curl_peer scaffolding introduced in
    later 8.x releases which is absent from 8.14.1. Instead, the
    equivalent client-credential keying is inlined into
    Curl_ssl_peer_key_make() directly, preserving the security fix
    without pulling in the test scaffolding.
