Description: CVE-2026-9080 - multi: handle pause in multi socket callback
 The mev_sh_entry object might be removed if curl_easy_pause() is called
 from within the socket callback. After invoking the socket callback,
 re-fetch the entry pointer since curl_easy_pause() (which is documented
 as callable from any callback) may re-enter mev_assess() and free the
 entry. A 'magic' struct field is also introduced to mev_sh_entry to
 detect/assert bad pointer dereferences in debug builds.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/curl/curl/commit/5ab34cba42e4ee4282fe8bab43f311d51b9bf9bd
Author: Daniel Stenberg <daniel@haxx.se>
Last-Update: 2026-05-26

--- a/lib/multi_ev.c
+++ b/lib/multi_ev.c
@@ -50,6 +50,8 @@ static void mev_in_callback(struct Curl_multi *multi, bool value)
 {
   multi->in_callback = value;
 }
 
+#define SH_ENTRY_MAGIC 0x570091d
+
 #define CURL_MEV_CONN_HASH_SIZE 3
 
@@ -64,5 +66,8 @@ struct mev_sh_entry {
                          * libcurl application to watch out for */
   unsigned int readers; /* this many transfers want to read */
   unsigned int writers; /* this many transfers want to write */
+#ifdef DEBUGBUILD
+  unsigned int magic;
+#endif
 };
 
@@ -85,5 +88,8 @@ static void mev_sh_entry_dtor(void *freethis)
 {
   struct mev_sh_entry *entry = (struct mev_sh_entry *)freethis;
   Curl_uint_spbset_destroy(&entry->xfers);
+#ifdef DEBUGBUILD
+  entry->magic = 0;
+#endif
   free(entry);
 }
 
@@ -122,7 +128,9 @@ static struct mev_sh_entry *mev_sh_entry_add(struct Curl_hash *sh,
     mev_sh_entry_dtor(check);
     return NULL; /* major failure */
   }
-
+#ifdef DEBUGBUILD
+  check->magic = SH_ENTRY_MAGIC;
+#endif
   return check; /* things are good in sockhash land */
 }
 
@@ -228,6 +236,7 @@ static CURLMcode mev_sh_entry_update(struct Curl_multi *multi,
 
   /* we should only be called when the callback exists */
   DEBUGASSERT(multi->socket_cb);
+  DEBUGASSERT(entry->magic == SH_ENTRY_MAGIC);
   if(!multi->socket_cb)
     return CURLM_OK;
 
@@ -282,11 +291,17 @@ static CURLMcode mev_sh_entry_update(struct Curl_multi *multi,
   rc = multi->socket_cb(data, s, comboaction, multi->socket_userp,
                         entry->user_data);
 
   mev_in_callback(multi, FALSE);
   if(rc == -1) {
     multi->dead = TRUE;
     return CURLM_ABORTED_BY_CALLBACK;
   }
-  entry->action = (unsigned int)comboaction;
+  /* curl_easy_pause() is documented as callable from any callback; it
+   * re-enters mev_assess() which may free this 'entry'. Re-fetch. */
+  entry = mev_sh_entry_get(&multi->ev.sh_entries, s);
+  if(entry) {
+    DEBUGASSERT(entry->magic == SH_ENTRY_MAGIC);
+    entry->action = (unsigned int)comboaction;
+  }
   return CURLM_OK;
 }
 
diff --git a/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..310d04c
--- /dev/null
+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,179 @@
+# False Positive Assessment: CVE-2025-10966 on Debian
+
+**CVE ID:** CVE-2025-10966
+**Package:** curl
+**Verdict:** FALSE POSITIVE — Not applicable to Debian builds
+**Date of Assessment:** March 30, 2026
+**Assessed by:** Security Engineering Team
+
+---
+
+## 1. Vulnerability Overview
+
+CVE-2025-10966 is a missing SFTP host verification vulnerability in libcurl affecting SSH-based
+file transfers performed via the wolfSSH backend.
+
+Official Description (curl Security Advisory, November 5, 2025):
+"When doing SFTP transfers, libcurl was not properly verifying the host key, making it possible
+for a man-in-the-middle attacker to trick curl into connecting to a different host than the
+intended one. This only affects builds using the wolfSSH backend."
+
+- CWE: CWE-322 — Key Exchange without Entity Authentication
+- Severity: Medium
+- CVSS Score: 4.3
+- Affected curl versions: 7.69.0 through 8.16.0 (inclusive)
+- Fixed in: curl 8.17.0 (released November 5, 2025)
+- Introduced in commit: 6773c7ca (curl 7.69.0)
+- Fixed by commit: b011e3fc (curl 8.17.0)
+- Fix method: wolfSSH backend support was COMPLETELY REMOVED from curl in 8.17.0
+
+---
+
+## 2. Root Cause Analysis
+
+The vulnerability exists exclusively in the wolfSSH integration layer of libcurl
+(source file: lib/vssh/wolfssh.c). When libcurl is built with wolfSSH as the SSH/SFTP backend,
+it fails to perform known_hosts validation and host key verification during SFTP transfers.
+
+This means an attacker in a Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) position can present a forged host key
+and libcurl will silently accept the connection — completely bypassing the intended host
+authentication mechanism.
+
+The curl team noted that wolfSSH was an incomplete, experimental backend that was almost never
+used in production. Rather than patching it, the decision was made to remove wolfSSH support
+entirely in curl 8.17.0.
+
+Critical Scope Statement (from Official curl Advisory):
+"This flaw only affects curl when built with the wolfSSH backend. Builds using libssh,
+libssh2, or any other SSH backend are not affected."
+
+This is the definitive reason this CVE is a false positive for Debian.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Why This Is a False Positive on Debian
+
+### 3.1 Debian Does Not Build curl With wolfSSH
+
+Debian compiles and ships its official curl packages WITHOUT wolfSSH support.
+
+The wolfSSH backend is a build-time opt-in feature (enabled via --with-wolfssh at compile time).
+Debian has never enabled this option in any of its curl package builds. As a result, the
+vulnerable source file lib/vssh/wolfssh.c is not compiled into any Debian curl binary —
+the vulnerable code path is physically absent.
+
+This is explicitly confirmed by the Debian Security Tracker for CVE-2025-10966:
+https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2025-10966
+
+Debian tracker note: "wolfSSH backend not used in Debian"
+
+### 3.2 wolfSSH vs. libssh2 — What Debian Actually Uses
+
+Debian builds curl using libssh2 as the SSH/SFTP backend — a completely separate, mature,
+and widely used SSH library that is not affected by this vulnerability.
+
+Property                       | wolfSSH                  | libssh2 (Debian)
+-------------------------------|--------------------------|---------------------------
+Project URL                    | https://www.wolfssl.com  | https://www.libssh2.org
+Maintained by                  | wolfSSL Inc.             | The libssh2 team
+Used by curl (Debian)          | NO                       | YES
+Experimental/incomplete        | YES                      | NO
+Affected by CVE-2025-10966     | YES                      | NO
+
+### 3.3 Debian Urgency Rating
+
+The Debian Security Tracker sets the urgency for this CVE as "unimportant" — a rating Debian
+uses specifically for issues that are not exploitable in the shipped configuration. This confirms
+there is no real risk for Debian systems.
+
+### 3.4 Other Distros Agree
+
+- Ubuntu: All releases marked "Not affected" — wolfSSH backend not used in Ubuntu curl builds.
+- Red Hat: Concluded "This flaw affects only curl when built with wolfSSH backend support"
+  and marked their products as not affected.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Affected Debian Versions — Scanner Report vs. Reality
+
+Debian Release         | Reported curl Version           | Scanner Status      | Actual Risk
+-----------------------|---------------------------------|---------------------|------------------------------
+Debian 11 (Bullseye)   | 7.74.0-1.3+deb11u13/u16         | Reported Vulnerable | NOT AFFECTED — no wolfSSH
+Debian 12 (Bookworm)   | 7.88.1-10+deb12u14/u5           | Reported Vulnerable | NOT AFFECTED — no wolfSSH
+Debian 13 (Trixie)     | 8.14.1-2+deb13u2                | Reported Vulnerable | NOT AFFECTED — no wolfSSH
+Debian Unstable (Sid)  | 8.17.0+                         | Fixed (wolfSSH removed upstream) | FIXED
+
+Note: For Bullseye, Bookworm, and Trixie, no backport is needed or planned since wolfSSH was
+never part of those builds. The vulnerability has zero attack surface on these systems.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Verification Steps
+
+To independently confirm this false positive on any Debian system:
+
+Step 1 — Check curl's linked SSH library:
+  curl -V
+
+Expected output on a standard Debian system will show libSSH2 and will NOT mention wolfSSH:
+  curl 7.88.1 (x86_64-pc-linux-gnu) libcurl/7.88.1 OpenSSL/3.0.x ... libSSH2/1.10.0
+
+The complete absence of "wolfSSH" in the output confirms the system is not affected.
+
+Step 2 — Inspect dynamic library links:
+  ldd $(which curl) | grep -i wolf
+
+Expected output: (nothing)
+
+A standard Debian system will return no output, confirming wolfSSH is not linked into curl.
+
+Step 3 — Check build flags (optional):
+  curl -V | grep -i Features
+
+The Features line will not include wolfSSH on any Debian system.
+
+---
+
+## 6. Comparison With CVE-2025-15079 (Same Pattern)
+
+Both CVEs are false positives for Debian for the same structural reason — a non-default,
+optional SSH backend that Debian simply does not compile into its curl packages:
+
+Property                              | CVE-2025-15079                             | CVE-2025-10966
+--------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------
+Affected backend                      | libssh                                     | wolfSSH
+Debian tracker note                   | "Debian builds with libssh2 for SSH backend" | "wolfSSH backend not used in Debian"
+Debian urgency                        | unimportant                                | unimportant
+Vulnerable code path in Debian curl?  | NO                                         | NO
+False positive for Debian?            | YES                                        | YES
+
+---
+
+## 7. Official References
+
+- curl Official Security Advisory:  https://curl.se/docs/CVE-2025-10966.html
+- Debian Security Tracker:          https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2025-10966
+- NVD Entry:                        https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2025-10966
+- curl Fix Commit (GitHub):         https://github.com/curl/curl/commit/b011e3fc
+- HackerOne Report:                 https://hackerone.com/reports/3355218
+- Ubuntu Advisory:                  https://ubuntu.com/security/CVE-2025-10966
+- Red Hat Advisory:                 https://access.redhat.com/security/cve/cve-2025-10966
+
+---
+
+## 8. Conclusion
+
+CVE-2025-10966 is a confirmed false positive for all official Debian curl packages on
+Bullseye (11), Bookworm (12), and Trixie (13).
+
+The vulnerability is strictly scoped to builds of libcurl that use the wolfSSH backend —
+an experimental, incomplete SSH library that was eventually removed entirely from curl in
+version 8.17.0. Debian has never compiled curl with wolfSSH support. The Debian Security Team
+has acknowledged this and marked the issue as "unimportant" in the tracker, explicitly noting:
+"wolfSSH backend not used in Debian."
+
+This finding should be suppressed or marked as a false positive in your vulnerability
+management system for all Debian hosts running the official Debian curl packages.
+
+---
+This document was prepared for internal vulnerability management purposes.
